1404
01:24:54,674 --> 01:24:56,968
Because a lot of times,
we would both do things.

1405
01:24:57,134 --> 01:24:58,761
- Right.
- You know, because...

1406
01:25:00,179 --> 01:25:02,265
...we wanted it to be me
and sometimes...

1407
01:25:02,431 --> 01:25:06,185
...there were things I couldn't do
as well as the stuntman...

1408
01:25:06,352 --> 01:25:08,312
- ...and we would both try it.
- Yeah.

1409
01:25:10,231 --> 01:25:13,526
And at first, you know,
I would be all gung ho and say:

1410
01:25:13,693 --> 01:25:15,152
"I wanna do it! I wanna do it!"

1411
01:25:15,319 --> 01:25:18,447
And they would be...
You know, Sam and Laura...

1412
01:25:19,657 --> 01:25:21,534
...would discourage me, you know:

1413
01:25:21,701 --> 01:25:25,371
"We don't really need you
to do this one and it's dangerous."

1414
01:25:25,538 --> 01:25:28,040
And by the end of the film
I was like:

1415
01:25:28,207 --> 01:25:32,295
- "No, just let him do it." You know?
- Yeah, "Bring in the double."

1416
01:25:32,461 --> 01:25:35,965
- Well, it was a long shoot for you.
- It was a very long shoot, yeah.

1417
01:25:38,592 --> 01:25:42,305
And I'll say, another person
behind the scenes...

1418
01:25:43,514 --> 01:25:46,225
...who really cares
about the character...

1419
01:25:46,976 --> 01:25:49,395
...and had a lot of great input
was Avi Arad...

1420
01:25:49,562 --> 01:25:54,233
...who's the head of... I believe
he's the head of Marvel Entertainment.

1421
01:25:54,400 --> 01:25:56,861
I mean, I don't know his actual title.

1422
01:25:57,570 --> 01:26:00,323
But, you know, these characters
are his babies.

1423
01:26:00,823 --> 01:26:06,287
And he just did a fine job
working with everybody on this movie.

1424
01:26:06,454 --> 01:26:10,416
And he's gotta be one of the most
prolific producers in Hollywood now...

1425
01:26:10,583 --> 01:26:13,002
...with all of his Marvel movies.
It's unbelievable.

1426
01:26:13,169 --> 01:26:16,505
And he's... The thing about Marvel...

1427
01:26:17,006 --> 01:26:19,091
...characters...

1428
01:26:19,925 --> 01:26:23,095
...is that they are relatable,
they are human. They're not...

1429
01:26:23,262 --> 01:26:25,681
...you know, perfect heroes...

1430
01:26:25,848 --> 01:26:28,517
...and just evil villains.

1431
01:26:28,684 --> 01:26:30,770
This was actually
one of the hardest stunts...

1432
01:26:30,936 --> 01:26:32,938
...just being up on that wall.

1433
01:26:33,105 --> 01:26:35,775
As hard as that... On the ceiling.
As hard as that...

1434
01:26:35,941 --> 01:26:38,110
And bleeding, always a drag
when they cut you...

1435
01:26:38,277 --> 01:26:40,571
- ...and you have to bleed.
- Right, of course.

1436
01:26:40,738 --> 01:26:44,325
Then you gotta rehydrate and you can't
take a potty break because of the suit.

1437
01:27:01,801 --> 01:27:05,137
- Great shot here too.
- Yeah.

1438
01:27:09,475 --> 01:27:12,103
- Hey, everyone.
- Oh, Peter!

1439
01:27:12,269 --> 01:27:15,981
Sorry I'm late, it's a jungle out there.
I had to beat an old lady with a stick...

1440
01:27:16,148 --> 01:27:19,026
Yeah, now, was that in the script,
or was that...?

1441
01:27:19,527 --> 01:27:23,906
I can't remember. I think it might have
been something Sam came up with.

1442
01:27:24,073 --> 01:27:28,035
It was really loose. You know,
going into this film, I'm thinking...

1443
01:27:28,202 --> 01:27:30,287
...you know, super big budget...

1444
01:27:31,539 --> 01:27:33,999
...you know, potential franchise...

1445
01:27:34,500 --> 01:27:38,754
...movie series for the studio.

1446
01:27:38,921 --> 01:27:42,842
It's gonna be really a lot of chefs
in the kitchen.

1447
01:27:43,008 --> 01:27:49,014
But they really gave us a tremendous
amount of freedom to play around.

1448
01:27:49,181 --> 01:27:51,016
That's what was great
about this film.

1449
01:27:51,183 --> 01:27:55,938
You know, I really went in going,
"Okay, be prepared for anything."

1450
01:27:56,105 --> 01:27:59,358
Because I hadn't done a film like this.
But it was the most freedom...

1451
01:27:59,525 --> 01:28:01,902
...I think I'd had on any film...

1452
01:28:02,069 --> 01:28:03,529
...which was pretty great.

1453
01:28:03,696 --> 01:28:06,949
I stepped off a curb and got clipped
by one of those bike messengers.

1454
01:28:07,116 --> 01:28:08,659
Well, let me see.

1455
01:28:08,868 --> 01:28:10,453
Oh, my goodness.

1456
01:28:10,619 --> 01:28:14,707
We discussed doing a Spidey-sense
moment here at the table.

1457
01:28:14,874 --> 01:28:17,710
But despite our budget,
we couldn't afford it.

1458
01:28:19,628 --> 01:28:21,380
That's the amazing thing
about movies.

1459
01:28:21,547 --> 01:28:23,883
No matter what the budget is,
it's never enough.

1460
01:28:24,049 --> 01:28:25,885
There's a top to it.

1461
01:28:26,051 --> 01:28:31,140
Whether you're on a 5-million-dollar...
I've been on $400,000 movies.

1462
01:28:31,307 --> 01:28:35,394
And this one that, you know, they
won't even tell you how much it cost.

1463
01:28:35,561 --> 01:28:37,271
And it's never enough.

1464
01:28:37,438 --> 01:28:39,732
- I've got to go.
- Why?

1465
01:28:40,149 --> 01:28:43,527
Something
has come to my attention.

1466
01:28:43,736 --> 01:28:44,987
Are you all right?

1467
01:28:45,571 --> 01:28:51,368
He has just discovered the identity
of Spider-Man.

1468
01:28:53,037 --> 01:28:56,582
I planned this so you'd meet M.J...

1469
01:28:56,874 --> 01:28:59,585
Well, I guess that's it, then.
Spider-Man's gonna be outed.

1470
01:28:59,793 --> 01:29:01,337
Yeah.

1471
01:29:01,504 --> 01:29:04,006
That's it. And here's...

1472
01:29:04,590 --> 01:29:08,177
...Harry Osborn
getting a little insensitive too.

1473
01:29:09,261 --> 01:29:14,475
Yeah, it's hard to confront
the old dad figure too much here.

1474
01:29:14,642 --> 01:29:17,019
- Yeah.
- He sort of loses his backbone.

1475
01:29:17,228 --> 01:29:18,521
You're wrong about her, Dad.

1476
01:29:19,021 --> 01:29:22,191
A word to the not-so-wise
about your little girlfriend:

1477
01:29:22,399 --> 01:29:25,069
Do what you need to with her,
then broom her fast.

1478
01:29:36,705 --> 01:29:39,208
Thanks for sticking up for me,
Harry.

1479
01:29:39,416 --> 01:29:42,378
- You heard?
- Everyone heard that creep.

1480
01:29:42,586 --> 01:29:46,465
That creep is my father.
With luck, I'll be half of what he is.

1481
01:29:46,715 --> 01:29:49,051
Shut up about stuff
you don't understand!

1482
01:29:49,218 --> 01:29:50,886
Harry Osborn!

1483
01:29:51,971 --> 01:29:54,014
I'm sorry, Aunt May.

1484
01:29:56,976 --> 01:30:00,312
<i>Spider-Man is all but invincible.</i>

1485
01:30:00,479 --> 01:30:03,649
<i>But Parker, we can destroy him.</i>

1486
01:30:03,816 --> 01:30:08,279
Getting advice from himself.
"Attack the heart."

1487
01:30:08,571 --> 01:30:10,823
<i>Parker must be educated.</i>

1488
01:30:12,992 --> 01:30:14,285
What do I do?

1489
01:30:14,827 --> 01:30:19,415
I think it's the merging of
the characters within himself. He's...

1490
01:30:22,042 --> 01:30:23,335
Yes?

1491
01:30:23,502 --> 01:30:28,674
He's starting to accept his... The evil
side is his more dominant side now.

1492
01:30:28,841 --> 01:30:32,011
<i>...Warrior attacks
neither body nor mind.</i>

1493
01:30:32,344 --> 01:30:33,512
Tell me how!

1494
01:30:33,679 --> 01:30:35,848
<i>The heart, Osborn.</i>

1495
01:30:36,098 --> 01:30:39,143
<i>First, we attack his heart.</i>

1496
01:30:42,938 --> 01:30:45,190
In this scene, Aunt May.

1497
01:30:45,357 --> 01:30:47,735
...And forgive us our trespasses...

1498
01:30:48,569 --> 01:30:52,740
Yeah, it's a great... The characters,
both Aunt May and Uncle Ben have...

1499
01:30:52,906 --> 01:30:56,368
...a great combination
of wisdom and innocence.

1500
01:30:56,535 --> 01:30:57,953
Yeah, absolutely.

1501
01:30:58,787 --> 01:31:02,249
And Uncle Ben is really kept alive...

1502
01:31:03,208 --> 01:31:08,255
...throughout the movie and throughout
the comic books he was too.

1503
01:31:13,594 --> 01:31:15,763
Two milligrams IV.

1504
01:31:17,556 --> 01:31:18,807
Get the BP.

1505
01:31:19,224 --> 01:31:22,811
Aunt May. Is she gonna be okay?
What happened?

1506
01:31:23,020 --> 01:31:24,355
You have to leave.

1507
01:31:24,521 --> 01:31:26,231
- What happened?
- Those eyes!

1508
01:31:26,440 --> 01:31:30,486
Those horrible yellow eyes!

1509
01:31:35,324 --> 01:31:37,868
He knows who I am.

1510
01:31:39,620 --> 01:31:41,789
Peter gets caught up.

1511
01:31:47,419 --> 01:31:51,590
Feeling responsible once again
for a loved one.

1512
01:31:51,757 --> 01:31:55,761
That was a great little shot there
of you actually saying the line:

1513
01:31:55,928 --> 01:31:58,472
"He knows who I am."
Because it was so important...

1514
01:31:58,639 --> 01:32:01,767
...to make that... Most people probably
would have understood that...

1515
01:32:01,934 --> 01:32:05,604
...with just what you were doing
with your face...

1516
01:32:05,771 --> 01:32:09,900
...but I'm sure Sam felt it was
important to make it very clear.

1517
01:32:10,067 --> 01:32:13,987
And it was good, I think,
not to bring back in the voice-over...

1518
01:32:14,154 --> 01:32:16,156
...idea too much
throughout the movie.

1519
01:32:16,323 --> 01:32:18,951
To just use that
as a kind of a bookend device.

1520
01:32:19,118 --> 01:32:25,416
Yeah. There was a lot of discussion
about when Peter should realize...

1521
01:32:26,792 --> 01:32:32,089
...that Norman figured it out.

1522
01:32:33,424 --> 01:32:36,176
- Thanks for coming.
- Of course.

1523
01:32:40,347 --> 01:32:43,267
How are you?
You okay about the other night?

1524
01:32:43,434 --> 01:32:47,104
Yeah, I'm fine. I just felt bad
about leaving Aunt May.

1525
01:32:47,354 --> 01:32:50,315
- Have you talked to Harry?
- He called me.

1526
01:32:50,774 --> 01:32:52,943
I haven't called him back.

1527
01:32:55,320 --> 01:32:59,658
Yeah, and here again in the middle of
this quote-unquote action movie...

1528
01:32:59,825 --> 01:33:04,246
...you know, we have a really nice
extended scene here...

1529
01:33:06,957 --> 01:33:09,334
...about the characters...

1530
01:33:09,752 --> 01:33:12,671
...and what's going on in their lives.

1531
01:33:12,838 --> 01:33:15,591
There's so many different...

1532
01:33:16,133 --> 01:33:17,384
It's funny.

1533
01:33:17,551 --> 01:33:19,803
...you know...

1534
01:33:19,970 --> 01:33:22,765
...stories going on within this.

1535
01:33:22,931 --> 01:33:28,687
And it's actually a pretty complex,
epic sort of film.

1536
01:33:30,272 --> 01:33:33,567
But do you think it's true, all the
terrible things they say about him?

1537
01:33:33,734 --> 01:33:37,070
That nice little shot of Aunt May
actually being awake now.

1538
01:33:37,237 --> 01:33:39,782
- Yeah, eavesdropping.
- Listening in to the whole thing.

1539
01:33:39,948 --> 01:33:42,409
I'm sort of his unofficial
photographer.

1540
01:33:42,701 --> 01:33:44,745
Which would be kind of skeevy...

1541
01:33:44,953 --> 01:33:47,664
...if it wasn't somebody
as sweet as Aunt May.

1542
01:33:49,416 --> 01:33:50,501
Here's...

1543
01:33:52,211 --> 01:33:57,549
...Peter getting himself
in a little bit of a pickle. Going into...

1544
01:33:57,716 --> 01:34:00,135
Speaking in third person
of his alter ego.

1545
01:34:00,302 --> 01:34:05,015
This is really one of the great romantic
little speeches here, though.

1546
01:34:05,182 --> 01:34:06,934
- It's really nice.
- Yeah, it was nice.

1547
01:34:07,100 --> 01:34:08,936
We did a lot of work on the dialogue.

1548
01:34:09,102 --> 01:34:11,730
It was very...

1549
01:34:12,397 --> 01:34:14,066
...tricky.

1550
01:34:16,443 --> 01:34:19,655
...And she's looking back in yours...

1551
01:34:20,155 --> 01:34:22,658
There it is. When you have...

1552
01:34:23,158 --> 01:34:27,120
...someone great to work with like
Kirsten, it makes it so much easier.

1553
01:34:27,287 --> 01:34:29,706
Right. Yeah, yeah, I mean, it's...

1554
01:34:29,873 --> 01:34:33,085
You're doing all the talking,
but it's so much a two-person scene.

1555
01:34:33,252 --> 01:34:35,796
- Yeah. Yeah.
- She contributes so much to it.

1556
01:34:35,963 --> 01:34:40,300
You can see her, like, progressively
opening and getting touched.

1557
01:34:40,467 --> 01:34:42,219
And then that...

1558
01:34:43,554 --> 01:34:46,932
...feeds me and informs my stuff.

1559
01:34:47,766 --> 01:34:52,062
The truth is, you don't know
what you feel...

1560
01:34:53,480 --> 01:34:57,109
...except you know what kind of man
you want to be.

1561
01:34:59,820 --> 01:35:01,697
It's as if you've...

1562
01:35:02,322 --> 01:35:05,492
...reached the unreachable...

1563
01:35:07,077 --> 01:35:09,788
...and you weren't ready for it."

1564
01:35:13,250 --> 01:35:15,002
You said that?

1565
01:35:15,794 --> 01:35:18,130
Well, something like that.

1566
01:35:18,797 --> 01:35:20,465
There's the little comic relief.

1567
01:35:20,632 --> 01:35:24,428
Yeah, little backpedal. "Yeah, you
know, something like that. Whatever."

1568
01:35:27,723 --> 01:35:31,476
It's great working with actors too,
and it's not always the case, where...

1569
01:35:31,643 --> 01:35:35,147
Obviously, when this scene is shot,
they point the camera on you...

1570
01:35:35,314 --> 01:35:38,150
...and do the whole scene,
then they turn everything around...

1571
01:35:38,317 --> 01:35:41,653
...take their four hours to light it,
and they point the camera on her.

1572
01:35:42,613 --> 01:35:44,489
But often times,
or at least sometimes...

1573
01:35:44,656 --> 01:35:47,743
...you work with other actors who,
when the camera's not on them...

1574
01:35:47,910 --> 01:35:50,787
...they kind of show up
and sit there and aren't really...

1575
01:35:50,954 --> 01:35:53,874
...contributing much
to what you're doing.

1576
01:35:54,041 --> 01:35:57,711
But it's obvious that you guys
were working for each other a lot.

1577
01:35:57,878 --> 01:36:00,797
Well, I've heard a lot of stories
about that kind of thing.

1578
01:36:00,964 --> 01:36:05,636
And I've been fortunate enough not to
have had to experience it too much.

1579
01:36:07,262 --> 01:36:12,184
Yeah, it's not... I mean, only
a few times that I've felt that way...

1580
01:36:12,351 --> 01:36:14,978
...about another actor.

1581
01:36:16,521 --> 01:36:18,607
Nobody in this movie.

1582
01:36:18,774 --> 01:36:20,442
No.

1583
01:36:21,652 --> 01:36:23,445
Well, you were right about M.J.

1584
01:36:23,737 --> 01:36:26,531
- Except for maybe Ted Raimi.
- Yeah, that guy. I don't know.

1585
01:36:26,698 --> 01:36:28,575
- How did he get the job?
- I don't know.

1586
01:36:28,742 --> 01:36:32,496
- What was the deal there?
- It was just a good audition, I think.

1587
01:36:32,663 --> 01:36:34,623
And how does he feel about her?

1588
01:36:37,209 --> 01:36:39,753
He's loved her since the 4th grade.

1589
01:36:40,712 --> 01:36:45,968
He pretends like he doesn't, but
there's no one Peter cares for more.

1590
01:36:47,427 --> 01:36:51,223
A little bonding moment
for father and son.

1591
01:36:51,390 --> 01:36:52,891
Yeah, they keep trying.

1592
01:36:53,058 --> 01:36:56,019
I haven't always been there for you,
Havel?

1593
01:36:58,313 --> 01:37:01,525
You're busy. You're an important man.
I understand.

1594
01:37:01,733 --> 01:37:03,527
That's no excuse.

1595
01:37:04,528 --> 01:37:06,321
I'm proud of you.

1596
01:37:06,863 --> 01:37:11,743
I've lost sight of that somewhere.
But I'll make it up to you.

1597
01:37:11,910 --> 01:37:15,247
I'm going to rectify
certain inequities.

1598
01:37:29,302 --> 01:37:31,096
<i>Wake up, little spider.</i>

1599
01:37:31,263 --> 01:37:32,764
Wake up.

1600
01:37:34,099 --> 01:37:35,684
Go home, dear.

1601
01:37:35,892 --> 01:37:37,227
You look awful.

1602
01:37:37,436 --> 01:37:39,730
- And you look beautiful.
- Well, thank you.

1603
01:37:39,938 --> 01:37:43,233
- I don't like to leave you here.
- But I'm safe here.

1604
01:37:43,400 --> 01:37:46,111
- Can I do anything for you?
- You do too much.

1605
01:37:46,278 --> 01:37:51,825
College, a job, all this time with me.
You're not Superman, you know.

1606
01:37:52,576 --> 01:37:54,327
A smile. Finally.

1607
01:37:54,494 --> 01:37:57,748
Haven't seen one of those on
your face since Mary Jane was here.

1608
01:37:57,914 --> 01:38:01,293
Hey.
You were supposed to be asleep.

1609
01:38:02,085 --> 01:38:06,882
You know, you were about 6 years old
when M.J.'s family moved in next door.

1610
01:38:07,090 --> 01:38:11,053
And when she got out of the car,
and you saw her for the first time...

1611
01:38:11,219 --> 01:38:14,639
It reminded me when she said
"you're not Superman" of the trailer.

1612
01:38:14,806 --> 01:38:19,311
I think the people who cut the trailer
in the Marketing Department...

1613
01:38:19,478 --> 01:38:23,440
...did such a good job, because
obviously the awareness was...

1614
01:38:23,607 --> 01:38:25,358
...very high.

1615
01:38:25,525 --> 01:38:29,154
But they also did a good job
of not giving away the entire movie.

1616
01:38:29,321 --> 01:38:32,616
Yes, which is a real pet peeve of mine.
It was a really good trailer.

1617
01:38:32,783 --> 01:38:36,578
- It was a good trailer.
- It gave you a real sense of it without...

1618
01:38:37,204 --> 01:38:38,914
Not giving away the whole thing, yeah.

1619
01:38:39,081 --> 01:38:41,833
Tell me, would it be so dangerous...

1620
01:38:42,042 --> 01:38:46,004
...to let Mary Jane know
how much you care?

1621
01:38:46,421 --> 01:38:48,924
Everybody else knows.

1622
01:38:51,968 --> 01:38:53,220
I'll be right back.

1623
01:38:53,887 --> 01:38:55,180
But...

1624
01:39:02,521 --> 01:39:04,523
Come on, pick up.

1625
01:39:04,689 --> 01:39:07,984
<i>- Hey, M.J...
- Sing your song at the beep.</i>

1626
01:39:09,069 --> 01:39:10,737
By the machine.

1627
01:39:11,363 --> 01:39:14,199
Hello? You there?

1628
01:39:14,699 --> 01:39:19,204
I'm just calling to check up on you.
Will you call me when you get in?

1629
01:39:19,371 --> 01:39:20,789
All right, well...

1630
01:39:20,956 --> 01:39:22,249
Don't...

1631
01:39:23,041 --> 01:39:25,252
Don't go up any dark alleys.

1632
01:39:25,460 --> 01:39:26,962
Hello?

